                    </image>
                    <p>Here again the <m>x - \text{axis}</m> is a horizontal asymptote, there is no <m>x -</m>intercept, 1 is <m>y -</m>intercept and the range is the set of positive real numbers. However, the graph is now decreasing rather than increasing.</p>
                    <p>The following box summarizes the important facts about exponential functions and their graphs.</p>
                    <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                        <col width="100%"/>
                    <row header="yes">
                    <cell><m>\textbf{The Exponential function}</m> <m>y = f(x) = b^{x}</m></cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                        <cell>
                            <p>
                                
                            <ol marker="1.">
                                <li><p>The domain of the exponential function is the set of real numbers</p></li>
                                <li><p>The range of the exponential function is the set of positive real numbers</p></li>
                                <li><p>The graph of <m>y = b^{x}</m> exhibits exponential growth if <m>b &gt; 1</m> or exponential decay if <m>0 &lt; b &lt; 1</m>.</p></li>
                                <li><p>The <m>y -</m>intercept is 1.</p></li>
                                <li><p>The <m>x -</m>intercept is a horizontal asymptote</p></li>
                                <li><p>The exponential function is 1 – 1. Algebraically if <m>b^{x} = b^{y}</m>, then <m>x = y</m></p></li>
                            </ol>
                          </p>
                      </cell>
