<example>
    <statement>
        <p> Sketch the graph of each of the following. Find the domain, range, intercepts, and asymptotes.</p>
        <p>
            a) <m>y = 3^{x} + 1</m>  <m> \qquad \qquad \text{b)}\,y = 3^{x + 1}</m> <m>\qquad \qquad \text{c)}\,y = - 9^{- x} + 3</m>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            <ol marker="a)">
                <li>
                    <p>To get the graph of <m>y = 3^{x} + 1</m>. We start with the graph of <m>y = 3^{x}</m>, which is the basic exponential growth graph, and shift it up 1 unit.</p>
                    <sidebyside>
                        <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image label="funct3">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                % Axes -------------------------------------------------
                                \draw[very thick,-&gt;] (-4,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {$x$};
                                \draw[very thick,-&gt;] (0,-0.5) -- (0,11) node[above] {$y$};

                                % Curve y = 3^x + 1 -----------------------------------
                                \draw[thick, smooth, samples=140, domain=-2:2.2, variable=\x]
                                        plot ({\x},{exp(\x*ln(3)) + 1});

                                % Horizontal asymptote y=1 ----------------------------
                                \draw[dashed] (-4,1) -- (3,1);
                                \node[above] at (3,1) {$y=1$};

                                % Dotted guide lines to (2,10) ------------------------
                                \draw[very thick,dashed, gray] (2,0) -- (2,10);
                                \draw[very thick,dashed, gray] (0,10) -- (2,10);

                                % Tick marks and labels ---------------------------------
                                \draw (1,0.15) -- (1,-0.15) node[below] {$1$};
                                \draw (2,0.15) -- (2,-0.15) node[below] {$2$};

