                    </sidebyside>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>To get the graph of <m>y = - 9^{- x} + 3</m>, we start with the basic exponential decay <m>y = 9^{- x}</m>. We then reflect it with respect to the <m>x - \text{axis}</m>, which gives the graph of <m>y = - 9^{- x}</m>. Finally, we shift this graph up 3 units to get the required graph of <m>y = - 9^{- x} + 3</m>.</p>

                    <image source="/media/curve.png">
                        <shortdescription>Basic exponential decay</shortdescription>
                    </image>

                    <p>From the graph of <m>y = - 9^{- x} + 3</m>, we can see that <m>\text{Dom}(h) = \Re</m>, <m>\text{Range}(h) = ( - \infty,3)</m>, the line <m>y = 3</m> is a horizontal asymptote, 2 is the <m>y -</m>intercept and <m>x = - \frac{1}{2}</m> is the <m>x -</m>intercept.</p>
                    <p><m>\textbf{Remark}</m>: When the base <m>b</m> of the exponential function <m>f(x) = b^{x}</m> equals to the number <m>e</m>, where <m>e = 2\text{.}\text{7182}\cdots</m>, we call the exponential function the natural exponential function.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>


<p>
    <ul>
    <li><p><m>\textbf{Logarithmic Functions}</m></p></li>
    </ul>
</p>

<p>In the previous subsection we noted that the exponential function <m>f(x) = b^{x}</m> (where <m>b &gt; 0</m> and <m>b \neq 1</m>) is one to one. Thus, the exponential function has an inverse function. What is the inverse of <m>f(x) = b^{x}</m>?</p>
<p>To find the inverse of <m>f(x) = b^{x}</m>, let’s review the process for finding an inverse function by comparing the process for the polynomial function <m>y = x^{3}</m> and the exponential function <m>y = 3^{x}</m>. Keep in mind that <m>x</m> is our independent variable and <m>y</m> is the dependent variable and so whenever possible we want a function solved explicitly for <m>y</m>.</p>

<tabular>
    <col width="100%"/>
    <row header="yes">
    <cell><m>\textbf{To find the inverse of}</m> <m>y = x^{3}</m></cell>
    <cell><m>\textbf{To find the inverse of}</m> <m>y = 3^{x}</m></cell>
    
    </row>

    <row>
    <cell><p><m>y = x^{3} \qquad \text{Interchange}</m> <m>x</m> and <m>y</m></p>
    <p><m>x = y^{3} \qquad \text{solve for}</m> <m>y</m></p></cell>
    <cell><p><m>y = 3^{x}\qquad \text{Interchange}</m> <m>x</m> and <m>y</m></p>
    <p><m>x = 3^{y} \qquad \text{solve for}</m> <m>y</m></p></cell>
    
    </row>
    <row>
        <cell><p><m>y=3\sqrt{x}</m></p></cell>
        <cell><p><m>y=\text{??}</m></p></cell>

    </row>
</tabular>

<p>There is no algebraic procedure we can use to solve <m>x = 3^{y}</m> for <m>y</m>. By introducing radical notations we could express the inverse of <m>y = x^{3}</m> explicitly in the form <m>y = \sqrt[3]{x}</m>. In words, <m>y^{3} = x</m> and <m>y = \sqrt[3]{x}</m> both mean exactly the same thing: <m>y</m> is the number whose cube is <m>x</m>. Similarly, if we want to express <m>x = 3^{y}</m> explicitly as a function of <m>x</m>, we need to invent a special notation for this. The key idea is to take the equation <m>x = 3^{y}</m> and express it verbally.</p>

<p>
    <me>
        x = 3^{y}\, \text{ means}\, y \, \text{ is the exponent to which}\, 3\, \text{ must be raised to yield}\, x
    </me>
    
</p>

<p>We introduce the following notation, which expresses this idea in a much more compact form.</p>

<definition xml:id="def-compacts">
    <statement>
        <p>
            For <m>b>0</m> and <m>b \neq 1</m>, we write <m>y = \log_{b} x</m> to mean <m>y</m> is the exponent to
            which <m>b</m> must be raised to yield <m>x</m>. In other words, <me>x = b^{y} \Leftrightarrow y = \log_{b} x</me>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>

<p>
    We read <m>y = \log_{b} x</m> as “<m>y</m> equals the logarithm of <m>x</m> to the base <m>b</m>”.
</p>
<p>
    <m>\textbf{REMEMBER:}</m> <m>y = \log_{b} x</m> is an alternative way of writing <m>x = b^{y}</m>
</p>

<p>When an expression is written in the form <m>x=b^{y}</m>, it is said to be in exponential form. When an expression is written in the form <m>y=\log_{b} x</m>, it is said to be in logarithmic form. The table below illustrates the equivalence of the exponential and logarithmic forms.</p>

<tabular halign="center"  left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
    <col width="100%"/>
<row header="yes">
<cell>Exponential form</cell>
<cell>Logarithmic form</cell>
</row>

<row>
<cell><p><m>4^2=16</m></p>
<p><m>2^4=16</m></p>
<p><m>5^{-3}=\frac{1}{125}</m></p>
<p><m>6^{\frac{1}{2}}= \sqrt{6}</m></p>
<p><m>7^{0}=1</m></p></cell>
<cell>
    <p><m>\log_{4} 16 = 2</m></p>
    <p><m>\log_{2} 16 = 4</m></p>
    <p><m>\log_{5} \frac{1}{125} = -3</m></p>
    <p><m>\log_{6} \sqrt{6} = \frac{1}{2}</m></p>
    <p><m>\log_{7} 1 = 0</m></p>
</cell>
</row>
</tabular>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Write each of the following in exponential form.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\log_{3}^ {\frac{1}{9}}=-2</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\log_{16} 2=\frac{1}{4}</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Write each of the following in logarithmic form.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>10^{-3}=0.001</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>27^{\frac{2}{3}}=9</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Evaluate each of the following.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\log_{3} 81</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\log_{8} \frac{1}{64}</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        We have
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\log_{3}^{\frac{1}{9}}=-2</m> means <m>3^{-2}=\frac{1}{9}</m>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    and
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\log_{16} 2=\frac{1}{4}</m> means <m>16^{\frac{1}{4}}=2</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        We have
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>10^{-3}=0.001</m> means <m>\log_{10} 0.001=-3</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>27^{\frac{2}{3}}=9</m> means <m>\log_{27} 9=\frac{2}{3}</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>

                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    To evaluate <m>\log_{3} 81</m>, we let <m>t = \log_{3} 81</m>, and then rewrite the equation in exponential
                                    form, <m>3^{t} = 81</m>. Now, if we can express both sides in terms of the same base, we can
                                    solve the resulting exponential equation, as follows:
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Let
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    
                                    <m>
                                        \begin{align}
                                        t &amp;= \log_{3} 81 \quad \text{ Rewrite in exponential form:} \\
                                        3^{t} &amp;= 81 \qquad \text{Express both sides in terms of the same base:} \\
                                        3^{t} &amp;= 3^{4} \qquad \text{Since the exponential function is }1 – 1 \\
                                        t &amp;= 4
                                        \end{align}
                                    </m>
                                    
                                    
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Therefore, <m>\log_{3} 81 = 4</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    We apply the same procedure as in part (a).
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Let
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\begin{align}
                                        t &amp;= \log_{8} \frac{1}{64} \quad \text{ Rewrite in exponential form:} \\
                                        8^{t} &amp;= \frac{1}{64} \qquad \text{Express both sides in terms of the same base:} \\
                                        8^{t} &amp;= 8^{-2} \qquad \text{Since the exponential function is }1 – 1 \\
                                        t &amp;= -2
                                        \end{align}
                                    </m>
                                    
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    Therefore, <m>\log_{8} \frac{1}{64} = -2</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        
    </solution>
</example>
<p>
    As was pointed out at the beginning of this subsection, logarithm notation was invented to
    express the inverse of the exponential function. Thus, <m>\log_{b} x</m> is a function of <m>x</m>. We usually
    write <m>f ( x ) = \log_{b} x</m> rather than writing <m>f ( x ) = \log_{b} ( x )</m> and use parenthesis only when needed to
    clarify the input to the log function. For example,
</p>
<p>
    If <m>f ( x ) = \log_{5} ( 4 - x )</m>, then <m>f ( -1) = \log_{5} (4 - ( -1)) = \log_{5} 5 = 1</m>, whereas if <m>f ( x ) = 4 - \log_{5} x</m>,
   then <m>f ( -1) = 4 - \log_{5} ( -1)</m>, which is undefined.
</p>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Given f<m>( x ) = \log_{5} x</m>, find
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>f(25)      \qquad \qquad \text{b)}\, f(\frac{1}{25}) \qquad \qquad \text{c)}\, f(0) \qquad \qquad \text{d)}\, f(-125)</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            <ol marker="a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                       <m>f(25)=log_{5} 25=2</m> (since <m>5^{2}=25</m>) 

                       
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>f(\frac{1}{25})=\log_{5} \frac{1}{25}=-2</m> (since <m>5^{-2}=\frac{1}{25}</m>)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>f(0)=\log_{5} 0</m> is not defined (what power of <m>5</m> will yield 0?). We say that <m>0</m> is not in
                        the domain of <m>f</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>f(-125)=\log_{5} -125</m> is not defined (what power of <m>5</m> will yield a negative number?). We say that
                        <m>-125</m> is not in the domain of <m>f</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>
<p>Acknowledging that the logarithmic and exponential functions are inverses, we can derive a great deal of information about the logarithmic function and its graph from the exponential function and its graph.</p>


<example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Sketch the graph of the following functions. Find the domain and range of each.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                       <m>y=\log_{3} x \qquad \qquad \text{b)}\, y=\log_{\frac{1}{2}} x</m> 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            <ol marker="a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Since <m>y = \log_{3} x</m> is the inverse of <m>y = 3^{x}</m>, we can obtain the graph of <m>y = \log_{3} x</m> by
                        reflecting the graph of <m>y = 3^{x}</m> about the line <m>y = x</m>, as shown below.
                    </p>
                    <image source="/media/Invers.png" >
                        <shortdescription>The first graph</shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        To get the graph of <m>y = \log_{1/2} x</m>, we reflect the graph of <m>y = (1/2)^{x}</m> about the line <m>y = x</m> as shown below.
                    </p>
                    <image source="/media/Reflect.png">
                        <shortdescription>The second graph</shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

<p>Taking note of the features of the two graphs we have the following important informations about the graph of the log function:</p>



<tabular halign="left"  left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
    <col width="100%"/>
<row header="yes">
<cell><m>\textbf{The Logarithmic Function}</m> <m>y=\log_{b} x</m></cell>
</row>

<row>
<cell>
    <p>
        
        <ol marker="1.">
        <li><p>Its domain is the set of positive real numbers</p></li>
        <li><p>Its range is the set of real numbers.</p></li>
        <li><p>Its graph exhibits logarithmic growth if <m>b>1</m> and logarithmic decay if <m>&lt;b&lt;1</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>The <m>x-</m> intercept is <m>1</m>. There is no <m>y-intercept</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>The <m>y-</m> axisis a vertical asymptote.</p></li>
    </ol>
</p>
</cell>
</row>
</tabular>


<example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Sketch the graph of <m>f(x)=1+\log_{3}(x-2)</m>. Find the domain, range, asymptote and
                        intercepts.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find the inverse function for
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>y=f(x=3^{x})+4   \qquad \qquad \text{b)}\, y=g(x)=\log_{3}(x-2)</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        We can obtain the graph of <m>y=1+\log_{3}(x-2)</m> by applying the graphing
                        principle to shift the basic logarithmic growth graph <m>2</m> units to the right and 1 unit up.
                    </p>
                    <image source="/media/Domain.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                    <p>
                        We have <em>Dom</em> <m>(f)={x:x>2}</m>, <em>Range</em><m>(f)={y:y>1}</m> and the graph has the line <m>x=2</m> as a
                        vertical asymptote. To find the intercept, we set <m>y=0</m> and solve for <m>x</m>. Setting <m>y=0</m>
                        and solving for <m>x</m>, we will obtain <m>x=\frac{7}{3}</m>. Thus, the <m>x-</m> intercept is <m>\frac{7}{3}</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Following the procedure for finding an inverse function, we have
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    We have
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow>y =\amp 3^x+4 \quad \text{Interchange}\, x \, \text{and}\, y </mrow>
                                        <mrow>x= \amp 3^y+4\quad  \text{solve explicitly for } \,y </mrow>
                                        <mrow>x-4= \amp 3^y \quad  \text{Write in logarithmic form} </mrow>
                                        <mrow>y= \amp \log_{3}(x-4) </mrow>
                                        <mrow>\text{Thus,}\,f^{-1}= \amp \log_{3}(x-4) </mrow>
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    We have
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow>y =\amp \log_{3}(x-2) \quad \text{Interchange}\, x \, \text{and}\, y </mrow>
                                        <mrow>x= \amp \log_{3}(y-2) \quad  \text{Write in logarithmic form} </mrow>
                                        <mrow> y-2= \amp 3^x\quad  \text{solve explicitly for } \,y </mrow>
                                        <mrow>y= \amp 3^x+2 </mrow>
                                        <mrow>\text{Thus,}\,g^{-1}= \amp 3^x+2 </mrow>
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>
<p>
    The following table contains the basic properties of logarithm:
</p>

<tabular halign="left"  left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" >
    <col width="100%"/>
    <row >
        <cell><p>
            <m>\textbf{Properties of logarithm}</m>
        </p></cell>
    </row>
    <row>
        <cell><p>
            Assume that <m>b</m>, <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> are positive and <m>b \neq 1</m>. Then
        </p></cell>
    </row>
    <row bottom="medium">
        <cell>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\log_{b}(uv) = \log_{b}(u) + \log_{b}(v)</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            In words, logarithm of a product is equal to the sum of the logs of the factors.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\log_{b}(\frac{u}{v}) = \log_{b}(u) - \log_{b}(v)</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            In words, the log of a quotient is the log of the numerator minus the log of the denominator.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\log_{b}(u^{r}) = r \log_{b}(u)</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            In words, the log of a power is the exponent times the log.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\log_{b}(b^{x}) = x \log_{b}(b) = x</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>b^{\log_{b} x} = x</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\log_{b}c=\frac{\log_{a}c}{\log_{a}b}</m> if a is positive and <m>a \neq 1</m> .
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </cell>
    </row>
</tabular>


<p>The following table contains the basic properties of logarithm:</p>
<example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Express in terms of simpler logarithms.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\log_{b}(x^3y)  \qquad \qquad \text{b)}\, \log_{b}(x^3+y) \qquad \qquad \text{c)}\, \log_{b}\left ( \frac{\sqrt{xy}}{z^3} \right )</m> 
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        
                        Show that <m>\log_{b} 12 = -\log_{b} 2</m>.
                    </p>
                    
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\log_{b}(x^3y) = \log_{b}x^3+log_{b}y=3\log_{b}(x) + log_{b}(y)</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Examining the properties of logarithms, we can see that they deal with log of a
                                    product, quotient and power. Thus, <m>log_{b}(x^3 + y)</m> which is the log of a sum cannot be
                                    simplified using log properties.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    We have
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\log_{b}\left ( \frac{\sqrt{xy}}{z^3} \right )=\log_{b}\sqrt{xy}-\log_{b}(z^3)=\log_{b}(xy)^\frac{1}{2}-3 \log_{b}z=\frac{1}{2}(\log_{b}x+\log_{b}y)-3\log_{b}z</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\text{We have}\, \log_{b} 12 = \log_{b} 1 - \log_{b} 2 = 0 - \log_{b} 2 = - \log_{b} 2 .</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>
<p>
    The logarithmic function was introduced without stressing the particular base chosen. However,
    there are two bases of special importance in science and mathematics, namely, <m>b = 10</m> and <m>b = e</m>.
</p>


<definition xml:id="def-common-logarithm">
    <statement>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{(Common Logarithm)}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>f ( x )=\log_{10} x</m> is called the common logarithm function. We write <m>\log_{10} x = \log x</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>
<p>
    The inverse of the natural exponential function is called the natural logarithmic function and has
    its own special notation.
</p>

<definition xml:id="def-natural-logarithm">
    <statement>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{(Natural Logarithm)}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>f ( x )=\log_{e} x</m> is called the natural logarithm function. We write <m>\log_{e} x = \ln x</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Evaluate <m>\log 1000</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find the inverse function of <m>f ( x ) = e^{x} + 1</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Evaluate <m>\log 1000</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                       Let <m>\log_{a}=\log 1000 </m>. Then , <m>a=\log_{10} 1000=\log_{10} 10^3=3</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            Let
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>
                \begin{align}
                 y &amp;=e^x+1 \qquad \text{Interchange x and y} \\
                 y &amp;=e^y+1 \qquad \text{Solve for }\,y \\
                 x-1 &amp;=e^y \qquad \qquad \text{Rewrite in logarithmic form}\\
                 y &amp;=\ln(x-1)\\
                 \text{Thus,}\,f^{-1} &amp;= \ln(x-1)
                \end{align}
            </m>
        </p>
        
    </solution>
</example>
<p>
    <ul>
    <li><p><m>\textbf{Trigonometric functions and their graphs}</m></p></li>
    </ul>
</p>



<p>For the functions we have encountered so far, namely polynomial, rational and exponential functions, as the independent variable goes to infinity the graph of each of these three functions either goes to infinity(very quickly) for exponential functions or approaches a finite horizontal asymptote. None of these functions can model the regular periodic patterns that play an important role in the social, biological, and physical sciences: business cycles, agricultural seasons, heart rhythms, and hormone level fluctuations, and tides and planetary motions.
    The basic functions for studying regular periodic behaviour are the trigonometric functions. The domain of the trigonometric functions is more naturally the set of all geometric angles.

</p>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Angle Measurement</title>
    <p>
        
    </p>
    <p>An angle is the figure formed by two half-lines or rays with a common end point. The common end point is called the vertex of the angle.</p>
    <image width="50%">
    <latex-image label="Trigo1">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
            \draw[->,very thick] (A) -- (6,0)node[right,pos=1.1]{} ;
            \draw[->,very thick] (A) -- (2,3) node[right,pos=1.1]{};
            \node[left] at (A) {\textbf{A}};
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
        
    </image>
    <p>
        In forming the angle, one side remains fixed and the other side rotates. The fixed side is called
        the initial side and the side that rotates is called the terminal side. If the terminal side rotates in a
        counter clockwise direction, we call the angle positive angle, and if the terminal side rotates in a
        clockwise direction, we call the angle negative angle.
    </p>
    <sidebyside>
        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="Trigo2">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Coordinates
                \coordinate (B) at (0,0);
                \coordinate (P) at (5,0);
                \coordinate (Q) at (4,3);

                % Vectors
                \draw[->,very thick] (B) -- (P);
                \draw[->,very thick] (B) -- (Q);

                % Labels
                \node[left] at (B) {\textbf{B}};

                % Manual arc between the vectors
                \draw[very thick,->]
                (1,0) arc[start angle=0,end angle=36.87,radius=1cm];

                % Text labels
                \node[rotate=40] at (2,2) {Terminal Side};
                \node[below] at (2.5,0) {Initial Side};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image >
        </image>
        
        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="Trigo3">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \coordinate (B) at (0,0);
                \coordinate (P) at (5,0);
                \coordinate (Q) at (4,3);
                \draw[->,very thick] (B) -- (P) ;
                \draw[->,very thick] (B) -- (Q) ;
                \node[above left] at (B) {\textbf{B}};
                \draw [->,very thick] (0.9,0.7)--(1.2,0);


                \node [rotate=38]at  (2,2){Initial Side};
                \node [below]at  (2.5,0){Terminal Side};

            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
    </sidebyside>
    <p>What attribute of an angle are we trying to measure when we measure the size of an angle? A moment of thought will lead us to the conclusion that when we measure an angle we are trying to answer the question: Through what part of a complete rotation has the terminal side rotated?</p>
    <p>We will use degree (°) as the unit of measurement for angles. Recall that the measure of a full round angle (full circle) is 360°, straight angle is 180°, and right angle is 90°.</p>
    <p>An alternative unit of measure for angles which will indicate their size is the radian measure.
         To see the connection between the degree measure and radian measure of an angle, let us consider an angle <m>\theta</m> and draw a circle of radius <m>r</m> 
    with the vertex of <m>\theta</m> at its 
    center <m>O</m>. Let <m>s</m> represent the
    length of the arc of the circle intercepted by <m>\angle \theta</m> (as shown below).</p>
    <image width="50%">
    <latex-image label="Trigo4">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Define coordinates
            \coordinate (B) at (0,0);
            \coordinate (P) at (5,0);
            \coordinate (Q) at (3,4);

            % Circle centered at B
            \draw[very thick] (B) circle[radius=3.5cm];

            % Vectors
            \draw[->,very thick] (B) -- (P); % initial side
            \draw[->,very thick] (B) -- (Q); % terminal side

            % Labels
            \node[left] at (B) {\textbf{O}};
            \node[below] at (2.5,0) {\textbf{r}};
            \node[] at (3.7,1.9) {\textbf{s}};  % terminal side label "r"
            \node at (1.5,0.5){$\huge{\theta}$};

            % Manual angle arc (approx. 36.87 degrees)
            \draw[very thick,]
            (1,0) arc[start angle=0,end angle=51,radius=1cm];
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
        
    </image>
    <p>Basic geometry tells us that the central angle <m>\theta</m> will be the 
    same fractional part of one complete rotation as <m>\textbf{s}</m> will be of the circumference of
    the circle. For example, <m>\theta</m> is <m>\frac{1}{10}</m> of
    a complete rotation, then <m>\textbf{s}</m> will be <m>\frac{1}{10}</m> of the circumference of the circle. In other words, we can set up the following proportion:</p>

    <p>
        <me>
            \frac{\theta}{1\,\textit{complete rotation}}=\frac{\textbf{s}}{\textit{circumference of circle}}=\frac{\text{s}}{2 \pi r}
        </me>
        
    </p>
    <p>
        Thus, we have the following conversion formula:
        <me>
            \frac{\theta\, \textit{in degrees}}{180^\circ}=\frac{\theta \, \textit{in radians}}{\pi}
        </me>
        
    </p>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Convert each of the following radian measures to degrees.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ol marker="a)">
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{\pi}{6}  \qquad \qquad \text{b)}\, \frac{3\pi} {5}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Convert to radian measures
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ol marker="a)">
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\frac{\pi}{6}  \qquad \qquad \text{b)}\, \frac{3\pi} {5}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol >
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <ol marker="a)">
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        By the conversion formula, we have <m>\frac{\theta}{180^\circ}=\frac{\frac{\pi}{6}}{\pi}</m>,
                                         which implies that <m>\theta=30^\circ</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Again using the conversion formula, we get <m>\frac{\theta}{180^\circ}=\frac{\frac{3 \pi}{5}}{\pi} </m>,
                                        which implies that <m>\theta=108^\circ</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <ol marker="a)">
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Let <m>\theta</m> represent the radian measure of <m>90^\circ</m>. Using the conversion formula, we
                                        obtain: <m>\frac{\theta}{\pi}=\frac{90^\circ}{180^\circ}</m>, which implies that <m>\theta=\frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Rather than using the conversion formula, we notice that <m>270^\circ=3(90^\circ)</m>.
                                        In part (a) we found that <m>90^\circ=\frac{\pi}{2}</m>, and so we have <m>270^\circ=3\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right)=\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
                                        
       
    <p>To define the trigonometric functions, we will view all angles in the context of
    a Cartesian coordinate system: that is, given an angle <m>\theta</m>, we begin by 
    putting <m>\theta</m> in standard position, meaning that the vertex of <m>\theta</m> is placed at the origin and initial side of <m>\theta</m> 
    is placed along the positive <em>x-axis</em>. Thus the location of the terminal side of <m>\theta</m> will, of course, 
    depend on the size of <m>\theta</m>.</p>

    <sidebyside>
        <image>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Axes
                \draw[&lt;->, very thick] (-3,0) -- (3,0) node[right] {$X$};
                \draw[&lt;->, very thick] (0,-3) -- (0,3) node[above] {$Y$};
                \draw [->,very thick](0,0) --(-3,2.5);

                
                
                \draw[very thick,->]
                            (0.5,0) arc[start angle=0,end angle=110,radius=1cm];
                \node [right] at (0.3,1.2){$\theta$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
            
        </image>
        <image>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                 % Axes
                \draw[&lt;->, very thick] (-3,0) -- (3,0) node[right] {$X$};
                \draw[&lt;->, very thick] (0,-3) -- (0,3) node[above] {$Y$};
                \draw [->,very thick](0,0) --(-3,3.5);

                % Point P(x,y)
                \filldraw (-2.5,2.9) circle (3pt) node[above right] {$P(x,y)$};
                
                \draw[very thick,->]
                            (0.5,0) arc[start angle=0,end angle=110,radius=1cm];
                \node [right] at (-1.5,1.2){\textbf{r}};

                \filldraw (0,0) circle (3pt);
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
            
        </image>
    </sidebyside>
    <p>We then locate a point (other than the origin) on the terminal side of 
    <m>\theta</m> and identify its coordinates <m>(x,y)</m> and its distance to the origin, 
    denoted by <m>r</m>. Then, <m>r</m> is positive.</p>
    <p>With <m>\theta</m> in standard position, we define the six trigonometric functions of <m>\theta</m> as follows:</p>

    <definition xml:id="def-trigonometric-functions">
        <statement>
            <tabular halign="center"  top="medium" >
                <col width="100%"/>
                <row header="yes" bottom="medium" >
                    <cell><p><m>\textbf{Name of function}</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\textbf{Abbreviation}</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\textbf{Definition}</m></p></cell>
                </row>
                <row >
                    <cell><p>Sine <m>\theta</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\sin \theta</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\sin \theta = \frac{y}{r}</m></p></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><p>Cosine <m>\theta</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\cos \theta</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\cos \theta = \frac{x}{r}</m></p></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><p>Tangent <m>\theta</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\tan \theta</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\tan \theta = \frac{y}{x}</m></p></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><p>Cosecant <m>\theta</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\csc \theta</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\csc \theta = \frac{r}{y}</m></p></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><p>Secant <m>\theta</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\sec \theta</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\sec \theta = \frac{r}{x}</m></p></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><p>Cotangent <m>\theta</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\cot \theta</m></p></cell>
                    <cell><p><m>\cot \theta = \frac{x}{y}</m></p></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
        Recall that the radian measure of an angle is defined as <m>\theta=\frac{s}{r}</m>, 
        where <m>s</m> is the length of the arc intercepted by <m>\theta</m> and <m>r</m> is the length of the radius
        Since <m>s</m> and <m>r</m> are both lengths, the quotient <m>\frac{s}{r}</m> is a pure number without any units attached. Thus, any angle can be interpreted as a real number. Conversely, 
        any real number can be interpreted as an angle. Thus, we can describe the domains of the trigonometric functions in the frame work of the real 
        number systems. If we let <m>f(x)=\sin \theta</m>, the domain consists of all real numbers <m>\theta</m> for which <m>\sin \theta</m> is defined.
        Since <m>\sin \theta=\frac{y}{r}</m> and <m>r</m> are never equal to zero, the domain for <m>\sin \theta</m> is the set of all real numbers.
        Similarly, the domain of <m>f(\theta) =\cos \theta=\frac{x}{r}</m> is also the set of all real numbers.
   </p>

   <p>
    <ul>
    <li><p><m>\textbf{The graph of} \,y=\sin \theta</m> </p></li>
    </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        To analyze <m>f{(\theta)}=sin{\theta}</m> , we keep in mind that once we choose a real number <m>\theta</m>, we draw the
        angle, in standard position, that corresponds to <m>\theta</m>. To simplify our analysis, we choose the point
        <m>(x,y)</m> on the terminal side so that <m>r=1</m>. That is, <m>(x,y)</m> is a point on the unit circle <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>.
        
        
    </p>
    <p>
        Note that <m>sin{\theta}=\frac{y}{1}=y</m>.
    </p>
    <image width="50%">
    <latex-image label="Trigo6">
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2, >=stealth]
            % Draw axes
            \draw[&lt;->,very  thick] (-1.5,0) -- (1.5,0);
            \draw[&lt;->,very  thick] (0,-1.5) -- (0,1.5);

            % Draw circle
            \draw[very thick] (0,0) circle (1);

            % Draw radius (angle)
            \draw[->, very thick] (0,0) -- (0.7,0.7);

            % Angle arc
            \draw [very thick](0.35,0) arc (0:45:0.35);
            \node at (0.5,0.15) {$\theta$};

            % Labels for unit circle points
            \node[above left] at (0,1) {$(0,1)$};
            \node[below left] at (0,-1) {$(0,-1)$};
            \node[below right] at (1,0) {$(1,0)$};
            \node[below left] at (-1,0) {$(-1,0)$};

            % Label for arbitrary (x,y)
            \node[above right] at (0.7,0.7) {$(x,y)$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
    </image>

    <p>
        As the terminal side of <m>\theta</m> moves through the first quadrant, <m>y</m> increases from <m>0</m> (when <m>\theta=0</m> ) to
        <m>1</m> (when <m>\theta=\frac{\pi}{2}</m> ). Thus, as <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>0</m> to <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>, <m>y=\sin{\theta}</m> steadily increases from <m>0</m> to <m>1</m>.
        As <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> to <m>\pi</m>, <m>y=\sin{\theta}</m> decreases from <m>1</m> to <m>0</m>. A similar analysis reveals that as
        <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>\pi</m> to <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>, <m>\sin{\theta}</m> decreases from <m>0</m> to <m>-1</m>; and as <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m> to <m>2\pi</m>,
        <m>\sin{\theta}</m> increases from <m>-1</m> to <m>0</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        Based on this analysis, we have the graph of <m>f (\theta ) = \sin{\theta}</m> in the interval <m>[0,2\pi ]</m> as show below.
    </p>
    <image width="70%">
    <latex-image label="Trigo5">
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2, >=stealth]
            % Axes
            \draw[very thick,->] (-1,0) -- (7,0) node[right] {$t$};
            \draw[very thick,->] (0,-1.5) -- (0,1.5) node[above] {$y$};

            % Sine curve
            \draw[very thick,domain=0:6.28, smooth, variable=\x, black, thick]
                plot ({\x}, {sin(deg(\x))});

            % X-axis labels in terms of pi
            \foreach \x/\label in {0/0, 1.57/$\frac{\pi}{2}$, 3.14/$\pi$, 4.71/$\frac{3\pi}{2}$, 6.28/$2\pi$}
                \draw[very thick] (\x,0.1) -- (\x,-0.1) node[below] {\label};

            % Y-axis labels
            \draw (0.1,1) -- (-0.1,1) node[left] {$1$};
            \draw (0.1,-1) -- (-0.1,-1) node[left] {$-1$};

            % Origin
            \node[below left] at (0,0) {O};
            

            % Function label
            \node[right, blue] at (2.5,1) {$y = \sin x$};
            \filldraw (0,0) circle (2pt);
            \filldraw (1.5,1) circle (2pt);
            \filldraw (3.15,0) circle (2pt);
            \filldraw (4.7,-1) circle (2pt);
            \filldraw (6.3,0) circle (2pt);
  
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
        
    </image>

    <p>
        Since the values of
        <m>f(\theta)=\sin \theta </m> depend only
        on the position of the
        terminal side, adding or
        subtracting multiples of
        <m>2\pi</m> to <m>\theta</m> will leave the
        unchanged. Thus, the
        value of <m>f(\theta)</m> will repeat every <m>2\pi</m> units. The complete graph of <m>f(\theta)</m> appears
        below.
    </p>

    <image width="70%">
    <latex-image label="Trigo7">
        \begin{tikzpicture}[xscale=0.5, yscale=2]
            % Axes
            \draw[->,very thick] (-13,0) -- (13,0) node[right] {$t$};
            \draw[->,very thick] (0,-1.5) -- (0,1.5) node[above] {$y$};

            % Ticks and labels on x-axis where sine crosses 0
            \foreach \x/\label in {-12.566/-4\pi, -6.283/-2\pi, 0/0, 6.283/2\pi, 12.566/4\pi} {
                \draw[thick] (\x,0.08) -- (\x,-0.08) node[below] {$\label$};
            }

            % Ticks and labels on y-axis
            \foreach \y in {-1,1} {
                \draw[thick] (0.2,\y) -- (-0.2,\y) node[left] {$\y$};
            }

            % Sine curve
            \draw[very thick,&lt;->, domain=-12.766:12.766, smooth, variable=\x] 
                plot ({\x}, {sin(\x r)});
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
        The graph of <m>y=\sin x</m>, which is called the basic sine curve.
    </p>

    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{The graph of} \, y=\cos \theta</m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        Applying the same type of analysis to <m>f(\theta) = \cos \theta</m>, we will able to get a good idea of what its
        graph looks like. The figure below shows the angle corresponding to <m>\theta</m> as it increases through
        quadrant I, II, III and IV.
    </p>
    <p>
        Keeping in mind that <m>\cos \theta = \frac{x}{1} = x</m>, we have the following:
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol marker="1.">
            <li>
                <p>
                    As <m>\theta</m> increases from 0 to <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>, <m>x = \cos \theta</m> decreases from 1 to 0.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    As <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m> to <m>\pi</m>, <m>x = \cos \theta</m> decreases from 0 to -1.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    As <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>\pi</m> to <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>, <m>x = \cos \theta</m> increases from -1 to 0.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    As <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>\frac{3\pi}{2}</m> to <m>2\pi</m>, <m>x = \cos \theta</m> increases from 0 to 1.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
        Based on this analysis, we have the graph of f (\theta ) = cos\theta as shown below:
    </p>
    <image width="70%">
