    This graph can also be obtained by geometrically adding the two curves <m>y = e^x</m> and <m>y =e^{-x}</m>, and taking half of each resulting <m>y</m>-value. Observe that range of <m>\cosh x</m> is <m>[1, \infty)</m>.
</p>
<p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{The graph of} \, y=\sinh x</m>
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</p>
<p>
    Since <m>\sinh\,x</m> is an odd function, its graph is symmetric about the origin. The graph passes
    through the origin because <m>\sinh(0) = 0</m>. As <m>x</m> gets large, <m>\sinh \,x</m> acts like
    <m>\frac{e^x}{2}</m> and when <m>x</m> is a large negative number, <m>\sinh \,x</m> acts like <m>-\frac{e^{-x}}{2}</m>.
    Thus, the graph of <m>y = \sinh \,x</m> looks like:
</p>


<image width="80%">
<latex-image label="Hyperbolic2">
    \begin{tikzpicture}
           \begin{axis}[
            axis lines=middle,
            xlabel={$x$},
            ylabel={$y$},
